text: Was thinking how Mickey Mouse's dog Pluto should be a more popular image in /x/ type paranormal and conspiracy theory circles because it's got the Hades symbolism in the name and also is named after an astrologically (and now astronomically) false planet.

Pluto is also the only true animal in a world of sentient humanlike animals so you have a "gnostic" aspect too or at least a "Eloi and Morlocks" Wellsian eugenics dystopia.  You would think Pluto the dog as a symbol would just appeal to the types that post on /x/ and such places.

Learning one new language is the equivalent to adding one plate to your bench

Some of the most intelligent people I know speak 5 or so languages. It changes your relationship to words and how your thoughts relate to language. The more monolingual you are, the more you are trapped into the particular cultural system you were born in without even knowing it.

I know someone into it but they have like 50 IQ points on me. From my perspective it seems like an almost perfect waste of time, but smart people are attracted to this type of stuff that seems ridiculous to others. Just stick to Spanish/German/French imo, no need to get too zany.

Did some early 19th century Farmers' Almanac suggest that you can treat a sick dog by giving him raw goat or sheep milk? How do so many American hickchuds seem to find the concept so intuitive? In Bulgarian literature they give bread or millet porridge to dogs to strengthen them.

At this point if I had a sheep or a goat I knew was healthy and eating good I would do the one month raw milk diet experiment on myself. I don't really have any limbs/body parts to regrow, but maybe my skull can expand to make room for more potential IQ or something.
For the record he recommended that method for a sort of apocalypse scenario where society breaks down and people revert to a Medieval type life so pharmacies no longer exist

I.e. tuberculosis sufferers had "Phthisical genius" that came with an impatient, irritable personality. A lot of these observations obviously didn't help patients, but were still correct. Nowadays we can cure tuberculosis, but no one could tell you how it affects the temperament.

Solving some big issues in medicine in the 20th century also meant a large loss of deeper complexity in the science. When tuberculosis was still impossible to treat, people had been forced to notice things like a "bilious temperament" being characteristic of tuberculosis patients

"The word plays an evil trick on those who have not mastered it. The writing dilettante does not understand the symbolic space created by his text and cannot develop or neutralize the symbols generated by it. He is a victim."

Dmitry Yevgenyevich Galkovsky
